1 (20) Public member. – A resident of North Carolina who is not a licensed
2 practitioner, does not perform medical imaging or radiation therapy
3 procedures under this Article, and is not affiliated with any group or
4 profession that provides or regulates health care or that may, in any way,
5 hinder the public member in representing the interest of the public.
6 (21) Radiation therapist. – A person who is licensed under this Article to perform
7 procedures involving the administration of external source ionizing radiation
8 to human beings for therapeutic purposes.
9 (22) Radiographer. – A person who is licensed under this Article to perform a
10 comprehensive set of diagnostic radiographic procedures using external
11 ionizing radiation to produce radiographic, fluoroscopic, or digital images.
12 (23) Radiologist. – A physician licensed under Article 1 of this Chapter who is
13 Board-eligible for certification or who is certified by the American Board of
14 Radiology, the American Osteopathic Board of Radiology, the British Royal
15 College of Radiology, or the Royal College of Physicians and Surgeons of
16 Canada.
17 (24) Radiologist assistant. – A licensed radiographer who is additionally licensed
18 under this Article to perform a variety of activities under the supervision of a
19 radiologist in the areas of patient care, patient management, and medical
20 imaging procedures.
21 "§ 90-752. License required; exemptions.
22 (a) License Required. – Except as provided in this section, only a person currently
23 licensed under this Article may perform or offer to perform radiologic imaging or radiation
24 therapy procedures on humans for diagnostic or therapeutic purposes or otherwise indicate or
25 imply that the person is licensed to perform radiologic imaging or radiation therapy procedures.
26 (b) License Required for Employment. – No person or business entity shall knowingly
27 employ a person who does not hold a license, or is not exempt under this Article, to perform
28 radiologic imaging or radiation therapy procedures on humans for diagnostic or therapeutic
29 purposes.
30 (c) No Limitation or Enlargement of Practice. – Nothing in this Article shall limit or
31 enlarge the practice of a licensed practitioner.
32 (d) Exemptions. – The provisions of this Article shall not apply to the following:
33 (1) A licensed practitioner performing medical imaging procedures or
34 administering radiation therapy.
35 (2) A registered dental hygienist (RDH).
36 (3) A dental assistant I or II who has satisfactorily completed one of the following:
37 a. The North Carolina radiography equivalency examination.
38 b. Dental assisting school through an American Dental
39 Association-accredited program.
40 c. The Dental Assisting National Board examination.
41 d. Classification as a dental assistant II in this State under the laws
42 regulating the practice of dentistry.
43 (4) A resident physician licensed under Article 1 of this Chapter.
44 (5) A student enrolled in and attending a school or college of medicine or medical
45 imaging or radiation therapy who performs medical imaging or radiation
46 therapy procedures on humans while under the supervision of a licensed
47 practitioner, or an individual holding a license under this Article.
48 (6) A person administering radiologic imaging or radiation procedures as an
49 employee of the United States government.
50 (7) A person performing radiologic procedures or therapy on cadavers.
