1 (c) The Board may provide for the late renewal of an automatically lapsed license upon
2 the payment of a reinstatement fee. The licensee shall maintain certification in his or her licensed
3 specialty throughout the licensure period established by the credentialing body.
4 (d) The Board may, upon application and payment of proper fees, issue a license to a
5 person who has been licensed, registered, or certified to perform medical imaging or radiation
6 therapy procedures in another jurisdiction if that jurisdiction's standards are substantially
7 equivalent to those provided in this Article and the regulations adopted by the Board.
8 "§ 90-761. Fees.
9 (a) The Board is authorized to charge and collect fees not to exceed the following:
10 (1) Initial, provisional, or temporary license application fee, one hundred dollars
11 ($100.00).
12 (2) Biennial license fee, one hundred fifty dollars ($150.00).
13 (3) Temporary license fee, one hundred dollars ($100.00).
14 (4) Duplicate license, twenty-five dollars ($25.00).
15 (5) License renewal late fee, seventy-five dollars ($75.00).
16 (b) All fees shall be set by the Board pursuant to rules adopted under this Article. All fees
17 payable to the Board shall be deposited in the name of the Board in financial institutions
18 designated by the Board as official depositories and shall be used to pay all expenses incurred in
19 carrying out the purposes of this Article.
20 (c) All salaries, compensation, and expenses incurred to carry out the purposes of this
21 Article shall be paid by the Board exclusively out of the fees received by the Board as authorized
22 by this Article or out of funds received from other sources.
23 "§ 90-762. Disciplinary authority.
24 (a) The Board may deny, suspend, revoke, or refuse to renew a license or impose
25 probationary conditions on a license if the licensee or applicant for licensure has engaged in any
26 of the following conduct:
27 (1) Obtaining a license by means of fraud, misrepresentation, or concealment of
28 material facts.
29 (2) Engaging in unprofessional conduct pursuant to rules adopted by the Board.
30 (3) Having been convicted of or pleaded guilty or nolo contendere to a crime
31 involving moral turpitude or any crime that indicates that the licensee or
32 applicant is unfit or incompetent to administer medical imaging or radiation
33 therapy procedures or that the licensee or applicant has deceived or defrauded
34 the public.
35 (4) Engaging in any act or practice in violation of any of the provisions of this
36 Article or any rule adopted by the Board or aiding, abetting, or assisting any
37 person in a violation.
38 (5) Committing an act or acts of malpractice, gross negligence, or incompetence
39 in administering medical imaging or radiation therapy procedures.
40 (6) Practicing as a person licensed to administer medical imaging or radiation
41 therapy procedures without a current license.
42 (7) Engaging in conduct that could result in harm or injury to the public.
43 (8) Being unfit or incompetent to administer medical imaging or radiation therapy
44 services by reason of deliberate or negligent acts or omissions, regardless of
45 whether actual injury to a patient is established.
46 (b) The denial, refusal to renew, suspension, revocation, or imposition of probationary
47 conditions upon a license may be ordered by the Board after a hearing held in accordance with
48 Chapter 150B of the General Statutes and rules adopted by the Board. An application may be
49 made to the Board for reinstatement of a revoked license if the revocation has been in effect for
50 at least two years after the date of the Board's order revoking the license.
51 "§ 90-763. Violation a misdemeanor; injunctive relief.
Senate Bill 415-First Edition Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (a) Any person who violates any provision of this Article shall be guilty of a Class 1
2 misdemeanor. Each act of such unlawful practice shall constitute a distinct and separate offense.
3 (b) The Board may make application to any appropriate court for an order enjoining
4 violations of this Article, and upon a showing by the Board that any person has violated or is
5 about to violate this Article, the court may grant an injunction or restraining order or take other
6 appropriate action."
7 SECTION 2. Notwithstanding the requirements of G.S. 90-754, as enacted by
8 Section 1 of this act, the initial appointees to the Medical Imaging and Radiation Therapy Board
9 of Examiners filling the membership positions for licensed radiologist, licensed nuclear medicine
10 technologist, licensed radiation therapist, and licensed sonographer do not have to meet the
11 licensure requirements established in Section 1 of this act, provided that these initial appointees
12 shall apply for and obtain a license from the Board within 90 days after the Board begins issuing
13 licenses.
14 SECTION 3. Persons other than radiologist assistants who have been engaged in the
15 practice of medical imaging and radiation therapy and who do not hold a current registration
16 from a voluntary professional certification organization approved by the Medical Imaging and
17 Radiation Therapy Board of Examiners may continue to practice in the modality of medical
18 imaging or radiation therapy in which they are currently employed provided that they (i) register
19 with the Board on or before October 1, 2026, (ii) do not change the scope of their current
20 employment practice, (iii) complete all continuing education requirements for their area of
21 practice annually as prescribed by the Board, and (iv) practice only under the supervision of a
22 radiologist.
23 SECTION 4. If any provision of this act or its application is held invalid, the
24 invalidity does not affect other provisions or applications of this act that can be given effect
25 without the invalid provisions or application and, to this end, the provisions of this act are
26 severable.
27 SECTION 5. The Medical Imaging and Radiation Therapy Board of Examiners may
28 adopt rules to implement the provisions of this act once the Board is appointed by the Governor
29 under this act.
30 SECTION 6. Section 1 of this act becomes effective January 1, 2026. The remainder
31 of this act is effective when it becomes law.
